fit a company makes after deducting the costs associated with making and selling its products, or the costs associated with providing its services.", "\"KEY PERFORMANCE INDICATORS (KPIS)\":\"Key performance indicators (KPIs) are measurable values that demonstrate how effectively a company is achieving its business objectives. KPIs are used to assess performance and guide strategic decisions.\"", "\"STRATEGIC PLANNING\":\"Strategic planning is the process of defining a company's direction and making decisions on allocating resources to pursue this direction. It involves setting objectives, analyzing competitive environments, and developing action plans.\"", "\"EMA TECHNIQUES\":\"EMA techniques include input/output analysis, ABC, and life-cycle costing.\"", "\"SUSTAINABILITY AND BUSINESS RESILIENCE\":\"Accountants must be able to link sustainability to the broader business agenda by highlighting elements that build resilience and develop a sustainable strategy.\"", "\"RELEVANT COSTS\":\"Relevant costs\" are costs that will be affected by a decision. In the context of further processing decisions, relevant costs include additional processing costs and any incremental revenues. They are used to determine the minimum price that can be used as the basis for a quotation. Relevant costs encompass those costs that are influenced by a specific management decision, including future costs and revenues, incremental costs, and cash flows.", "\"OPPORTUNITY COSTS\":\"Opportunity costs\" are the benefits foregone by choosing one alternative over another. They represent the potential benefits an individual, investor, or business misses out on when making a choice between different options.", "\"MAKE-OR-BUY DECISIONS\":\"Make-or-buy decisions involve comparing the costs and benefits of producing goods or services in-house versus outsourcing.\"", "\"INCREMENTAL COSTS\":\"Incremental costs\" are the additional costs incurred if a particular decision is made. These costs arise when a company decides to increase its level of activity, such as further processing a product or continuing in-house production of components like keypads and display screens. Incremental costs include both variable and attributable fixed costs and are crucial for decision-making as they directly impact the profitability of the decision.", "\"AVOIDABLE COSTS\":\"Avoidable costs are those which would be avoided if a particular course of action were taken.\"", "\"CONTROLLABLE COSTS\":\"Controllable costs are those that can be influenced by the actions of the person who controls the budget or cost center.\"", "\"QUIZ: INCREMENTAL COSTS\":\"This quiz involves identifying whether each cost in a wedding event scenario is incremental or not.\"", "\"SUNK COSTS\":\"Sunk costs are historical costs that have already been incurred and cannot be recovered. Examples include research and development costs already incurred and market research.\"", "\"COMMITTED COSTS\":\"Committed costs are future costs that a company has already committed to, such as contract rental and lease payments. These costs are not incremental and are irrelevant to decision-making unless the contract is cancellable.\""], "parameters": {"model": "text-embedding-3-small", "temperature": 0.0, "frequency_penalty": null, "presence_penalty": null, "top_p": 1.0, "max_tokens": 4000, "n": 1}}